  "text": "The Prometheus TSDB head block handles series limits and out-of-order/out-of-bounds sample validation through a multi-layered architecture:\n\n## Series Limit Enforcement\nIn `tsdb/head.go`, the `getOrCreateWithOptionalID()` function (lines 1844-1874) enforces series creation limits via the `SeriesLifecycleCallback.PreCreation()` hook (line 1845). This callback is defined in the `SeriesLifecycleCallback` interface (lines 234-242) and can be implemented by external users to reject series creation when cardinality limits are exceeded. Note that Prometheus itself uses a no-op callback by default but provides the hook for users who import TSDB to enforce their own limits.\n\n## Out-of-Bounds and Out-of-Order Sample Handling\nSample validation occurs in the append path through multiple mechanisms:\n\n### Fast-path rejection (head_append.go and head_append_v2.go)\n- In `headAppender.Append()` (line 425-431) and `headAppenderV2.Append()` (line 127-132), samples with timestamps before `minValidTime` are immediately rejected with `ErrOutOfBounds` when OOO support is disabled.\n\n### Detailed validation per-series (head_append.go)\nThe `appendable()` function (lines 639-683) performs comprehensive checks on float samples:\n- If timestamp >= minValidTime: sample is in-order, permitted for in-order chunk\n- If timestamp < minValidTime but oooTimeWindow > 0: sample is evaluated for OOO chunk (lines 671-673)\n- If sample falls outside both windows: \n  - With OOO enabled: returns `ErrTooOldSample` (line 677)\n  - With OOO disabled and t < minValidTime: returns `ErrOutOfBounds` (line 680)\n  - With OOO disabled and t >= minValidTime but still out-of-order: returns `ErrOutOfOrderSample` (line 682)\n\nHistogram-specific variants (`appendableHistogram` lines 688-725 and `appendableFloatHistogram` lines 730+) implement the same logic for histogram samples.\n\n## Key Error Types (storage/interface.go)\n- `ErrOutOfBounds`: Sample timestamp is too old (before minValidTime) with OOO support disabled (lines 35-36)\n- `ErrOutOfOrderSample`: Sample is out-of-order when OOO support is disabled (lines 33-34)\n- `ErrTooOldSample`: Sample is outside the OOO time window when OOO support is enabled (defined implicitly through appendable return values)\n\n## Metrics Tracking\nThe Head block metrics (lines 384-390, 469-515 in head.go) track:\n- `outOfBoundSamples`: Counter for rejected out-of-bounds samples\n- `outOfOrderSamples`: Counter for rejected out-of-order samples  \n- `tooOldSamples`: Counter for samples outside OOO time window\n\n## Out-of-Order Head Block\nWhen OOO support is enabled (oooTimeWindow > 0), out-of-order samples are stored in a separate OOO head block structure (`tsdb/ooo_head.go`) rather than being rejected. This structure maintains separate chunks for out-of-order samples that don't fit the normal in-order append pattern, allowing Prometheus to handle late-arriving samples from distributed systems.\n\nThe validation chain flows: Append() → getOrCreate() [series creation with PreCreation callback] → appendable() [sample timestamp validation] → storage in in-order or OOO chunks depending on timestamp and configuration."
}

